section.para:
			The detector works on any character sequence. In the text below, the word
			cafÃ© is the UTF-8 form of a word read through a
			single-byte decoding, and � is a replacement character left
			by a failed decode:

ArtifactDetector detector = new CursorArtifactDetector();
String text = "cafÃ© costs �8";

for (TextArtifact artifact : detector.detect(text)) {
    System.out.println(artifact.type() + " " + artifact.span());
}

			This prints one line per finding, with exact offsets into the original text:

mojibake [3..5)
replacement [12..13)

			Ordinary accented words are not mojibake: their single-byte images are not
			valid UTF-8 sequences, so a text like déjà vu yields no
			finding at all.
			ArtifactsManualExampleTest asserts the behavior shown here.
